text.text:
Course Face-off: Fit or Bit

Welcome to our Course Face-off series where two academics back their course in a winner-takes-all battle for supremacy.

text_498580732.text: Dr Mark Merolli [left] and Dr James Hamlyn-Harris [right] stand back to back.

text_745380948.text:
“You are going to get me in so much trouble,” says Dr Mark Merolli, Academic Director of Digital Health and Informatics at Swinburne.

No, no. We’re just putting you in the arena. You’ll be the one doing all the sledging.

“So, who am I up against?”

The Bachelor of Computer Science. You know – cybersecurity, software development, the internet of things, data science...  

“Is it really fair on them to be going up against us?”

And, with that, before the first bell has even rung, Dr Merolli goes in below the belt. The fight is on. Welcome to the big card event…

text_1734613677.text:
BACHELOR OF HEALTH SCIENCE

(Major in Digital Health and Infromatics)

vs

BACHELOR OF COMPUTER SCIENCE

(Major in Cybersecurity)

text_1132705379.text: In the Computer Science corner, and bringing with him an outstanding background in cybersecurity (he even runs a club), is Dr James Hamlyn-Harris. Annnnd, in the Health Science corner, rocking sensational knowledge of Digital Health and something called Informatics, is Dr Mark Merolli.

text_942128529.text: James takes a load off during the gruelling debate with Mark.

text_51298450.text: Which graduates do we need more of?

text_1385116275.text:
Mark: Look, It’s pretty hard to have a conversation about 21st century health without thinking about technology.

James: That’s right, the courses really go hand-in-hand. The more digital health technology we have, the bigger the risks of cyber-attacks. So, as these areas grow, more opportunities open up for graduates from these programs.

Mark: Yes, so that means loads of jobs in medical technology, data, consulting, research, planning and policy.

James: And, of course, there are massive shortages in cybersecurity predicted. We’re talking shortages of several million people across the globe by 2025. Then, if you want to go totally buzzword compliant, there’s also huge opportunities in big data, internet of things, and data science.

You know you guys are meant to be fighting, right?

Mark: Pretty sure we agree that these areas are thoroughly intertwined?

James: Yep. Jobs for all.

Well, after that nauseating consensus, let’s hope these two actually land a blow or two in the next question.

Mark: Before we get to that. What I really want to say is the digital health and informatics graduates will be the ones shaping the agenda for what the computer scientists actually need to be working on.

James: Oh, I see! Well, without computer science you health professionals wouldn’t have all the sweet gear we’ve built. You know, all that life-saving technology.

And, we’re back. Thank you.

text_463205082.text: Who’s going to have a greater impact on the world?

text_1947818342.text: Go on, Mark you take first crack at this one.

text_2066993290.text:
Mark: Well, you don’t study any health science major without caring about people and their well-being. Digital health and informatics actually enables you to take care of individuals, and the wider community at a public health level. Our graduates become real advocates and drivers of change. There’s a fire that burns inside them.

James: They should probably see a doctor.

Mark: Funny.

James: Let’s kick this up a notch. The annual Global Risks Report from the World Economic Forum listed the top 10 risks likely to happen in the next decade. And, this year, cyberattacks infiltrated the top three.

Yikes. So, like hacking an AI piloted drone or a digital pace-maker? Or… the use of technology to spread misinformation… ie. ‘Fake news’.

James: Yep.

Not so much of the bawdy banter we were all hoping for there, more of the: ‘Hey, the end of the world is nigh and the only ones who can save you are cybersecurity ninjas.’ Thanks James.

And, as far as health science is concerned, well health science has always been a pretty amazing life saver… except for that dark period when the cure-all ‘tech’ of choice was a leech or two.

text_1955750673.text: Mark and James appear to be getting along… Finally.

text_1595464126.text: Who’s more likely to get a date?

text_1689326380.text:
Mark: Oh, well the answer is obvious. The digital health graduate will. I’m not sure talking to a computer all day will help the cybersecurity analyst get a date.

Oof, a big swipe there. Digital Health and Informatics unleashing some serious heat at the Computer Science team with a slightly dated reference to the stilted social skills of an IT professional. What’s James coming back with?

James: Well, cybersecurity professionals basically have to be hackers. They’re called ‘white hat’ hackers, or ethical hackers. To properly assess a system’s vulnerability to cyberattack, they have to actually know how to break into them… Now, if that doesn’t make them cool, their bushy hipster beards or micro-fringes do.

Surely Mark has to concede to the revolution – renaissance even – of the nerd, here?

Mark: I do. In all honesty, I really love the marriage between computer and health science.

James: Yep, the internet of things is another big cross-over point. Did you know there are sensors you can swallow that provide data about your body to health professionals?

Mark: How cool is that!

Alright, Alright. Break it up. Seems like we’ve wound our way back to a consensus here... What a shame. 

We’ll call this a tie as its clear there are pretty good reasons to take on either the Bachelor of Computer Science (major in Cybersecurity) or the Bachelor of Health Science (major in Digital Health and Informatics)…
